description:
Circle and dive into the sea! My first time witnessing an osprey fishing, and I had my camera on me. I had a manual focus lens on, but I had a couple of seconds while it was preparing to dive. Then, fell quickly and hit the water with a big splash. It seemed like it was under water for quite awhile, but according to the camera, it was only 2 seconds. Looks like no catch this time. It flew all the way to the island pictured after the attempt.

I was standing in a playground next to the seashore with maybe 20 other people around. I think I was the only one to notice this, as I looked around me afterwards. Quite an amazing experience to see!

In the 2 months following this, I've noticed 4 individual ospreys in the vicinity. Looking forward to capturing more from these beautiful birds.

description:
Group of 5 birds, 4 very small and fluffy and one larger bird—a Dunlin? see here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70138939

The plovers ran around and between each other, so I can't tell them apart. They are lumped in one observation.

The birds seemed to be a group, even flying off together, looping around a large circle and back to another part of the beach.

Are these plovers adult females? They show no rufus coloring on head and no black on the eye stripe or neck ring.

One Dunlin in a group of 4 Kentish Plovers on the beach.

Calidris alpina sakhalina? Observed in Japan, plumage is more plain grey and while, lacks any black on underparts.

Plovers in a separate observation:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70084345

Same individual Great Egret here:

https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70494985

The Grey Heron wasn't bothered by the Little Egret, but it got in the way. Little Egret here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70495502

description:
Black-eared Kite loses its prey (duck) when attacked by two corvids. A heron follows in the distance.

I was standing on the street, just getting out of the car and ready to begin my planned walk with camera in hand, and had kind of noticed some noisy birds off in the distance. The sound from behind me got closer suddenly and so I turned quickly, pulling my camera up to my eye, and saw a confused flutter of wings coming right at me at high speed. I managed to snap a few shots blindly and the carcass landed on the road just a couple of steps away. The birds flew off. There were children around, so I picked up the carcass and tossed it down onto the river bank next to the road out of sight. At the end of my walk, a couple of hours later, I returned to the same place and found the carcass still there. Apparently, none of the birds fighting over it won.

description:
A Black-eared Kite (Milvus migrans lineatus) #トビ loses its prey when attacked by two crows. An egret follows in the distance.

I was standing on the street, having just finished a conversation, getting ready to begin my planned walk with camera in hand. and had kind of noticed some noisy birds off in the distance. The sound from behind me got  closer suddenly and so I turned quickly, pulling my camera up to my eye,  and saw a confused flutter of wings coming right at me at high speed. I managed to snap a few shots blindly and the carcass landed on the road  just a couple of steps away. The birds flew off. There were children  around, so I picked up the carcass and tossed it down onto the river bank next to the road out of sight. At the end of my walk, a couple of  hours later, I returned to the same place and found the carcass still  there. Apparently, none of the birds fighting over it won.

Kite observation here:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/72675205
